## Problem statement

Swagger too deep scans.  It finds too many declarations. 
1. These declarations are not necessary. 
2. Deep scan is causing the error.
## Steps to reproduce

```
//go:generate swagger generate spec
package main

import (
    mgo "gopkg.in/mgo.v2"
)

type BodyParamType struct {
    A string
    B int
}

// swagger:parameters myOperation
type ParamType struct {
    // in:body
    InBody BodyParamType
}

type SomeType struct {
    Session    *mgo.Session
    Parameters ParamType
}

// swagger:route POST /path myAPI myOperation

func main() {

}

```

run:
    swagger generate spec main.go

result is the error:
    **Expr (pathToGoPath/src/gopkg.in/mgo.v2/session.go:386:13) is unsupported for a schema**
## Suggestions

See in file "scan/scanner.go", line 291
    func (a *appScanner) processDiscovered() error

It calls ("scan/scanner.go", line 303)
    if err := a.parseSchema(sd.File); err != nil {

Func parseSchema is trying to parse the **whole file**. 
And loop "for keepGoing" ("scan/scannner.go", line 294) parses all declarations recursively.

That is unnecessary.
Suffice it to receive information only on **specific type**. Variable "a.discovered" contains that already. See "scan/scanner.go", line 293 (in begin of processDiscovered()")

In this example, information is needed about the BodyParamType, but does not require information about SomeType and (recursively) about mgo.Session.

go-swagger is very pointer happy it still has an issue for patching objects because with pointers because we don't know if it was actually a value that was set or if it was a value that's nil.

So i think this will have to change one more time to use nullable types where set/unset is a property on the type. 

That keeps GC pressure lower, but I think that might create a need for 2 structs. 
One is the binding/validating struct and the second one is the one the user actually uses because a nullable type would kind of look like

``` go
type NullableBool struct {
  value bool
  IsNull bool
  WasSet bool
}

func (n *NullableBool) Value() *bool  {
  if n.IsNull {
    return nil
  } 
  return &n.value
}
```

The biggest benefit we derive from this is the ability to do patches on objects

## Problem statement

It would be useful if it was possible to specify constants within the spec. I know the recommended practice is to use an enum with 1 value, but this will only _validate_ inputs. A given client is unable to reference the possible values or know what the appropriate default is.  I've experimented a little with using extensions, but the long and the short of it is that I ultimately have to write a factory for each model object to properly initialize the values. It would be much more convenient if I could somehow define constants or a constructor inside the spec.
## Swagger specification

```
"VersionClusterState" : {
            "type" : "object",
            "required" : [ 
                "major",
                "minor",
                "patch"
            ],
            "properties" : {
                "major" : {
                    "type" : "integer",
                    "enum" : [ 1 ] 
                },
                "minor" : {
                    "type" : "integer",
                    "enum" : [ 1 ]
                },
                "patch" : {
                    "type" : "integer",
                    "enum" : [ 0 ]
                }
            }
        }
```
## Client

```
// returns Major, Minor, Patch = 0, useless
func DefaultVersionClusterState() *models.VersionClusterState {
        &models.VersionClusterState{}
}

// returns initialized object, but pain in the ass and defeats purpose. Given the choice to modify spec and code, I'll just modify code instead
func NewVersionClusterState() *VersionClusterState{
        var spec = spec.New(restapi.SwaggerJSON, "").Extensions[]... //read custom extensions from spec
        &models.VersionClusterState{spec.Major, spec.Minor, spec.Patch}
}

//easier but error prone and hard for developers to manage versions
func NewVersionClusterState() *VersionClusterState{
        &models.VersionClusterState{1, 1, 0}
}
```

I'm curious if it's possible to improve this behaviour. Ideally something like adding a factory method that would supply an object with its default values based on the spec.
